Inflation in Europe has jumped because of food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, annual inflation was registered 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, reported by the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, reported by Bloomberg.
Unlike US, British, and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the basic interest rate, with the decrease in raw material prices and falling unemployment leading to an inflation spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2%, but close to it.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a preposterous situation: it must 'serve' inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation represents 3.3 percent of a 15-year record; in Spain it then rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to rising food and energy prices.
The term wheat prices have risen by 88 percent, as well as the soy exchange rate has reached the highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007, it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The world market price has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will shift from 2.1% to 2.5% this year in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double the interest rates during 2008.
