In many places they save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hospital hygiene conditions, bed overcrowding, overburdens of personnel do not help with disease control, claims the head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many places also save money on disinfectants.
Recently, the trauma department of St. John's Hospital has been diagnosed with MRSA infection.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who got into the hospital after a serious accident.
The patient's been isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after that he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria found in his organism there could not be one important operation.
By 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant disease agents were reported to the Nesocomialis Surveillance National System, said Karolina Böröczová, the head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant disease agents have been safely registered in hospitals, others are not known.
Almost two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methhicillin-oxacillin resistant to gold staphylococci.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carry a third of the people in their nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsilitis, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, when antibiotics are administered excessively or inappropriately, they develop a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, in the case of temporary or permanent poor functioning of the immune system in patients with weakened organism, low body weight or in patients over the years, serious hospital infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning, may cause sepsis.
According to the chief physician at St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are among the daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the disease agent is not investigated."
Resisting Antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, care personnel treat them in rubber gloves, and mask, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined for presence in their MRSA organism, but infection is not always avoided.
Sampling is not in mode
Most hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favourable for preventing the emergence and spread of multi-resistant disease agents, claims Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection is typically found in hospitals and homes for elderly people, hospitals should immediately control the patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers.
However, the collection of microbiological samples is not in the fashion of Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role.
Most cases are revealed when the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also home guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
In order to avoid drug resistance, antibiotic therapy should be targeted, or microbiological tests should be carried out, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases.
The collection of microbiological samples is even more rare for basic and outpatient treatment, as reported by Karolina Böröczová.
Saved for disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads among patients most often through medical personnel.
This is why washing hands and using gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in hospitals there are serious shortcomings.
MRSA is transmitted by drip infection and touch, but in the conditions of home hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
The rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröczová noted, unfortunately we can also see that in hospitals that are in an unfavourable material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few caregivers and many patients, thus increasing the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are being observed, similar infections are demonstrably less likely or further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its occurrence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistent disease agents (including MRSAs), respectively hospital infections caused by these disease agents, among its priorities.
