Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
On Friday in Budapest, the Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajeck, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed an agreement on three credit frameworks worth EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects implemented under the support of the Cohesion Fund, with the parties having already concluded a loan agreement of EUR 100 million, the Treaty now signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
Also, the EUR 150 million loan agreement is used for the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for these purposes, and the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million, which will be used primarily for the research-development project of the University of Debrecín.
At the meeting there was also a talk about the 4th metro line.
The Parties agree that, once Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the financing of the metro, it will return to whether and how the original agreement needs to be modified.
According to János Veres, this can happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of EUR 8.4 billion of 113 projects in Hungary.
The interest on loans granted by the EIB with an eight-year waiting period and no commitment commission shall be linked to the EURIBOR rate.
