Fodor and Hungarian 6 percent
According to information from the Minister of the Environment and Water Management Gábor Fodor, the meetings of experts will be closed on Tuesday and after the official opening of Wednesday, the international conference on the climate regime will continue after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world are discussing the Bali Travel Map, which addresses efforts following the period of emission reduction as defined by the Kyoto Protocol in force until 2012.
At this point, there is a heated debate between developing and advanced countries.
The United States has also announced that they do not want to discuss precise figures now, although they are inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020, given the 1990 status.
Another major issue of the conference is whether advanced countries will, in addition to reducing emissions, also agree to provide both material and technological assistance to countries that rely on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by the 16-member Governing Board, most likely within the framework of the World Environmental Protection Programme (GEF) at the UN - we can read in the Piac és Profit magazine.
Hungarian 6 percent
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Water Management, Gábor Fodor, supports the EU's efforts to maintain a leading role in efforts to protect the global climate and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990, independently of the success of adopting the post-2012 'agreement', and is prepared to commit to a reduction of up to 30% if other developed regions of the world, or developed countries, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments appropriate to their capabilities.
Gabor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set the target of a 5.2 percent reduction, with 15 EU Member States making an 8 percent commitment.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87, which our country will fulfil. - It is mentioned in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
Bali is a big deal, because an international agreement on long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would certainly not be postponed until 2012. In such a case, a new emission reduction system would not immediately follow up on the reduction commitments set by the Kyoto Protocol, the need for which the UN International Climate Change Scientific Council has also pointed out in its latest report - the IPCC, a Nobel Peace Prize winner.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and an inevitable increase in the average temperature on Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
