Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased country risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of Jobbik Magyarszágért in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute, increased the political risk of Hungary and the whole area in several respects.
The "risk warning" drawn up by the company states: in connection with the Hungarian Guard's activities, the greatest political risk is that "the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Roma populations of Hungary may be exacerbated by violent ethnic clashes in a short time".
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is probably aimed at provoking such an action - supplied by the research institute.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the biggest negligence of Hungarian political leaders: 'public debate on the Roma issue was left to representatives of public life of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict'.
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - the Institute judges.
In addition, according to the research institute, the Hungarian Guard's activities were "to a large extent corrupted the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity".
The Institute recalls: part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which have been getting ever more publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, is that several organizations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, which are called "national militias" themselves.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civic associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defence tasks (in the event of natural disasters, assault of their homeland, disruption of order), plus pointing to the inability of the police, army, or state," he adds.
He further notes: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap up various political efforts based on the opposition of society to politics and parties into civilian robes.
Therefore, emphasising civility and the form of association in the case of these groupings is not only designed to avoid legal difficulties in judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the Hungarian Guard’s activity is also a risk-enhancing factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard is being referred to in several neighbouring states as a potential source of danger, and ultra-nationalist political representatives of some neighbouring countries want to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policy by appealing to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All of this can affect the political stability of the area," he adds.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guards in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so political risks to the area as a whole have increased.
As he writes, the Hungarian Guard’s activity is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the ultra-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
Against the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard there are mass Romani riots that broke out in one of the Sofia districts (Krasna Poljana).
She used this BNU to set up a guard, saying that the organization's goal is "national militia".
