Congress approved MiFID transposition valid from 1 November
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the vote of Congress on amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government subjected the new law to a public hearing with a view to both of them entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties have consistently highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities needed for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the different supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial consultancy services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons, and will create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial consultancy companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities brokering offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of operations with financial instruments is expanding by connecting multilateral trading and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
Furthermore, the Act obliges investment service providers to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of dealing with risk, and requires a statement of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the hearing in the Congress Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which were outstanding, for securitised claims to be considered a "complicated" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the US with high risk mortgage debt (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the directive was used to legally define the functions that bachelors in the field of economics and corporate governance can hold for 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which sets out professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as a broker who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
