Concerns about the new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
The dispute over gas prices is currently under way between Russia and Ukraine, so the risk of Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe is increasing.
Most of Russia's fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is pipelined across Ukraine, and any dispute between these two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raised gas prices to Ukraine, Russia would charge higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between these two last year reduced deliveries to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says he will have to charge Ukraine more because he has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas he receives from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its deliveries from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," said the Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatoli Kinach to Reuters.
"Changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees (to Western Europe) via Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in deliveries from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This has caused an overwhelming fall in exports to Western Europe, which has sharply increased prices.
Russian gas represents one quarter of the supply to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of them remain under-utilised.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
NHS "must control foreign employees"
The supervisor said that the Scottish NHS Chamber must improve the control of criminal records of non-European employees.
A recommendation from the president of Robert Black's Supreme Audit Office came after a foreign doctor operating in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Mr. Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS has no precise idea of the number of foreign personnel he employs.
But his report pointed out that the other key checks were carried out in order on a sample of five health authorities.
The president of the Supreme Audit Office was immediately interested in personnel from countries outside the European Economic Area following the June attacks at Glasgow Airport.
22-year-old Bilal Abdullah, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after someone drove a Jeep into the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of being connected to attempted bombings in the UK.
The NHS Chambers are expected to check foreign personnel in terms of qualifications, experience and authorisation for work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Commission uses Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, this agency has no authority to obtain such information outside Britain.
A report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other things, that the Commission should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau guidelines, which help employers with checks in several countries.
"Although we have discovered that part of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly," the report announced.
Mr Black said that the Scottish NHS is much in line with its own policy of pre-employee checks, but he also added: "Our report draws attention to areas in which the system could be improved to ensure the availability of accurate information on the number of foreign personnel."
President of BMA Scotland Dr. Peter Terry said that it is "very unlikely" that pre-employee controls would identify potential NHS employees who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employee controls in the Scottish NHS work well and it is not clear what further value these comments will bring," he said.
The Scottish health authorities have announced that they currently have 1 161 foreign workers, most of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office pointed out that these figures would probably be higher, too, because the Commission had difficulty identifying personnel with residence permits.
The survey also found that the established control procedures for NHS authorities in the areas of Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely carried out.
They included passport checks, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently revamping the policies and directives of pre-employee controls for NHS foreign workers.
Minister of Health Nicola Sturgeon said: "I wanted to handle this work immediately after the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It also added that the Scottish Government, in line with the health commissions, will consider the recommendations of this report and ensure that the best practices appear in the updated directives of the pre-employee controls of all personnel - including the foreign one - which it plans to issue next month.
