The climate of Venus can be seen in the future of the Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus could once have been a pleasant place to live.
The data from the orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more like the headstrong twin Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit similar paths, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the effluent greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and lower rate of rotation sent Venus along a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is waterless, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead and be ravaged by storms and hurricane winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency’s probe Venus Express, which studied the planet for one year, offer a modest view of how the Earth could develop in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics of Oxford University and one of the Heads of Mission Venus Express said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different than on Earth, although the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to build a scenario in which Venus began, like Earth, perhaps even with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
