Does the US credit card market affect the subprime mortgage crisis?
When there's blood in the water, naturally the dorsal fins begin to wave aroused.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is wasting away, predators have targeted the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs analysts say that losing on credit cards could reach $99 billion if subprime mortgages infected other consumer credit options.
The signs of tension are clear.
There is an increase in the number of cases of inability to repay (at more than 30 days late payment) and written-off accounts (accounts considered by the provider to be unenforceable).
HSBC announced last month that it lost $1.4 billion on the US consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it is still too early to panic.
There is still little written-off accounts and inability to repay.
According to Moody's evaluation agency, 3.89% of the insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below the average.
The worsening rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in the US law on personal bankruptcy in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which make a large part of the credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore rise, regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers worsened.
The sector also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts per month.
And trust in credit card securities is solid, despite paralysis in other parts of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney from TowerGroup's research firm predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% larger than last year.
Direct ways to spread infections between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: when real-estate loans dry up, consumers tend to owe themselves over credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, look at cash flow rather than the value of guarantee items, so falling home prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They may even be advantageous for loan providers.
Consumer incentive to repay mortgages falls when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; consequently, credit on cards is shifted up to the list of priorities for repayment.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to stormier conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid change in the price of guarantee items.
"It doesn't happen that one beautiful morning we'll just re-evaluate all the loans," says Gary Perlin, Chief Financial Officer of Capital One.
Even if the risk of a subprime mortgage explosion is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
